# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gcp-apigee
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gcp-apigee/api] An **application programming interface** (**API**) is a connection between computers or between computer programs.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] It is a type of software interface, offering a service to other pieces of software.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] A document or standard that describes how to build such a connection or interface is called an *API specification*.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] A computer system that meets this standard is said to *implement* or *expose* an API.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] The term API may refer either to the specification or to the implementation.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] In contrast to a user interface, which connects a computer to a person, an application programming interface connects computers or pieces of software to each other.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] It is not intended to be used directly by a person (the end user) other than a computer programmer who is incorporating it into software.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] An API is often made up of different parts which act as tools or services that are available to the programmer.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] A program or a programmer that uses one of these parts is said to *call* that portion of the API.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] The calls that make up the API are also known as subroutines, methods, requests, or endpoints.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] An API specification *defines* these calls, meaning that it explains how to use or implement them.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] One of the main purpose of APIs is to hide the internal details of how a system works, exposing only those parts a programmer will find useful and keeping them consistent even if the internal details later change.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] An API may be custom-built for a particular pair of systems, or it may be a shared standard allowing interoperability among many systems.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] The term API is often used to refer to web APIs, which allow communication between computers that are joined by the internet.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] There are also APIs for programming languages, software libraries, computer operating systems, and computer hardware.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] APIs originated in the 1940s, though the term did not emerge until the 1960s and 70s.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] An API opens a software system to interactions from the outside.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] It allows two software systems to communicate across a boundary — an interface — using mutually agreed-upon signals.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] In other words, an API connects software entities together.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Unlike a user interface, an API is typically not visible to users.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] It is an "under the hood" portion of a software system, used for machine-to-machine communication.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] A well-designed API exposes only objects or actions needed by software or software developers.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] This abstraction simplifies programming.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Building software using APIs has been compared to using building-block toys, such as Lego bricks.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Software services or software libraries are analogous to the bricks; they may be joined together via their APIs, composing a new software product.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] The process of joining is called *integration*.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] As an example, consider a weather sensor that offers an API.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] When a certain message is transmitted to the sensor, it will detect the current weather conditions and reply with a weather report.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] The message that activates the sensor is an API *call*, and the weather report is an API *response*.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] A weather forecasting app might integrate with a number of weather sensor APIs, gathering weather data from throughout a geographical area.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] It represents an agreement between parties: a service provider who offers the API and the software developers who rely upon it.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] If the API remains stable, or if it changes only in predictable ways, developers' confidence in the API will increase.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] The term *API* initially described an interface only for end-user-facing programs, known as application programs.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] This origin is still reflected in the name "application programming interface." Today, the term is broader, including also utility software and even hardware interfaces.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] The idea of the API is much older than the term itself.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] British computer scientists Maurice Wilkes and David Wheeler worked on a modular software library in the 1940s for EDSAC, an early computer.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] The subroutines in this library were stored on punched paper tape organized in a filing cabinet.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] This cabinet also contained what Wilkes and Wheeler called a "library catalog" of notes about each subroutine and how to incorporate it into a program.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Today, such a catalog would be called an API (or an API specification or API documentation) because it instructs a programmer on how to use (or "call") each subroutine that the programmer needs.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Wilkes and Wheeler's book *The Preparation of Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer* contains the first published API specification.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Joshua Bloch considers that Wilkes and Wheeler "latently invented" the API, because it is more of a concept that is discovered than invented.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] The term "application program interface" (without an *-ing* suffix) is first recorded in a paper called *Data structures and techniques for remote computer graphics* presented at an AFIPS conference in 1968.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] The authors of this paper use the term to describe the interaction of an application—a graphics program in this case—with the rest of the computer system.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] A consistent application interface (consisting of Fortran subroutine calls) was intended to free the programmer from dealing with idiosyncrasies of the graphics display device, and to provide hardware independence if the computer or the display were replaced.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] The term was introduced to the field of databases by C.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Date in a 1974 paper called *The Relational and Network Approaches: Comparison of the Application Programming Interface*.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] An API became a part of the ANSI/SPARC framework for database management systems.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] This framework treated the application programming interface separately from other interfaces, such as the query interface.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Database professionals in the 1970s observed these different interfaces could be combined; a sufficiently rich application interface could support the other interfaces as well.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] This observation led to APIs that supported all types of programming, not just application programming.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] By 1990, the API was defined simply as "a set of services available to a programmer for performing certain tasks" by technologist Carl Malamud.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] The idea of the API was expanded again with the dawn of remote procedure calls and web APIs.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] As computer networks became common in the 1970s and 80s, programmers wanted to call libraries located not only on their local computers, but on computers located elsewhere.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] These remote procedure calls were well supported by the Java language in particular.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] In the 1990s, with the spread of the internet, standards like CORBA, COM, and DCOM competed to become the most common way to expose API services.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] XML and JSON web APIs saw widespread commercial adoption beginning in 2000 and continuing as of 2021.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] The web API is now the most common meaning of the term API.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] The Semantic Web proposed by Tim Berners-Lee in 2001 included "semantic APIs" that recast the API as an open, distributed data interface rather than a software behavior interface.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Proprietary interfaces and agents became more widespread than open ones, but the idea of the API as a data interface took hold.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Because web APIs are widely used to exchange data of all kinds online, API has become a broad term describing much of the communication on the internet.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] When used in this way, the term API has overlap in meaning with the term communication protocol.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] The interface to a software library is one type of API.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] The API describes and prescribes the "expected behavior" (a specification) while the library is an "actual implementation" of this set of rules.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] A single API can have multiple implementations (or none, being abstract) in the form of different libraries that share the same programming interface.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] The separation of the API from its implementation can allow programs written in one language to use a library written in another.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] For example, because Scala and Java compile to compatible bytecode, Scala developers can take advantage of any Java API.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] API use can vary depending on the type of programming language involved.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] An API for a procedural language such as Lua could consist primarily of basic routines to execute code, manipulate data or handle errors while an API for an object-oriented language, such as Java, would provide a specification of classes and its class methods.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] By mapping the features and capabilities of one language to an interface implemented in another language, a language binding allows a library or service written in one language to be used when developing in another language.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Tools such as SWIG and F2PY, a Fortran-to-Python interface generator, facilitate the creation of such interfaces.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Moreover, the overall program flow of control can be out of the control of the caller and in the framework's hands by inversion of control or a similar mechanism.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] An API can specify the interface between an application and the operating system.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] POSIX, for example, specifies a set of common APIs that aim to enable an application written for a POSIX conformant operating system to be compiled for another POSIX conformant operating system.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Linux and Berkeley Software Distribution are examples of operating systems that implement the POSIX APIs.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Microsoft has shown a strong commitment to a backward-compatible API, particularly within its Windows API (Win32) library, so older applications may run on newer versions of Windows using an executable-specific setting called "Compatibility Mode".
[src:gcp-apigee/api] How much Microsoft developers' access to the company's operating systems' internal APIs is an advantage is unclear.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Shaffer of *Technologic Computer Letter* in 1987 compared the situation to a baseball game in which "Microsoft owns all the bats and the field", and large vendors like Lotus Development and Ashton-Tate reportedly received information about MS-DOS 5.0 that smaller software developers did not.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Ed Esber of Ashton-Tate said in a 1987 interview, however, that Bill Gates told him that his developers sometimes had to rewrite software based on early APIs.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Gates noted in the interview that Microsoft's Apple Macintosh applications were more successful than those for MS-DOS, because his company did not have to also devote resources to Mac OS.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] An API differs from an application binary interface (ABI) in that an API is source code based while an ABI is binary based.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] For instance, POSIX provides APIs while the Linux Standard Base provides an ABI.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Remote APIs allow developers to manipulate remote resources through protocols, specific standards for communication that allow different technologies to work together, regardless of language or platform.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Therefore, remote APIs are useful in maintaining the object abstraction in object-oriented programming; a method call, executed locally on a proxy object, invokes the corresponding method on the remote object, using the remoting protocol, and acquires the result to be used locally as a return value.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] A modification of the proxy object will also result in a corresponding modification of the remote object.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Web APIs are the defined interfaces through which interactions happen between an enterprise and applications that use its assets, which also is a Service Level Agreement (SLA) to specify the functional provider and expose the service path or URL for its API users.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] An API approach is an architectural approach that revolves around providing a program interface to a set of services to different applications serving different types of consumers.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] An example might be a shipping company API that can be added to an eCommerce-focused website to facilitate ordering shipping services and automatically include current shipping rates, without the site developer having to enter the shipper's rate table into a web database.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Part of this trend is related to the Semantic Web movement toward Resource Description Framework (RDF), a concept to promote web-based ontology engineering technologies.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Web APIs allow the combination of multiple APIs into new applications known as mashups.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] In the social media space, web APIs have allowed web communities to facilitate sharing content and data between communities and applications.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] In this way, content that is created in one place dynamically can be posted and updated to multiple locations on the web.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] For example, Twitter's REST API allows developers to access core Twitter data and the Search API provides methods for developers to interact with Twitter Search and trends data.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] The design of an API has significant impact on its usage.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] The principle of information hiding describes the role of programming interfaces as enabling modular programming by hiding the implementation details of the modules so that users of modules need not understand the complexities inside the modules.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Thus, the design of an API attempts to provide only the tools a user would expect.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] The design of programming interfaces represents an important part of software architecture, the organization of a complex piece of software.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] APIs are one of the more common ways technology companies integrate.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Those that provide and use APIs are considered as being members of a business ecosystem.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] An important factor when an API becomes public is its "interface stability".
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Changes to the API—for example adding new parameters to a function call—could break compatibility with the clients that depend on that API.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] When parts of a publicly presented API are subject to change and thus not stable, such parts of a particular API should be documented explicitly as "unstable".
[src:gcp-apigee/api] For example, in the Google Guava library, the parts that are considered unstable, and that might change soon, are marked with the Java annotation `@Beta`.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] A public API can sometimes declare parts of itself as *deprecated* or rescinded.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] This usually means that part of the API should be considered a candidate for being removed, or modified in a backward incompatible way.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Therefore, these changes allow developers to transition away from parts of the API that will be removed or not supported in the future.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Client code may contain innovative or opportunistic usages that were not intended by the API designers.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] In other words, for a library with a significant user base, when an element becomes part of the public API, it may be used in diverse ways.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] On February 19, 2020, Akamai published their annual “State of the Internet” report, showcasing the growing trend of cybercriminals targeting public API platforms at financial services worldwide.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] From December 2017 through November 2019, Akamai witnessed 85.42 billion credential violation attacks.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] About 20%, or 16.55 billion, were against hostnames defined as API endpoints.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Of these, 473.5 million have targeted financial services sector organizations.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] API documentation describes what services an API offers and how to use those services, aiming to cover everything a client would need to know for practical purposes.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Documentation is crucial for the development and maintenance of applications using the API.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] API documentation is traditionally found in documentation files but can also be found in social media such as blogs, forums, and Q&A websites.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Traditional documentation files are often presented via a documentation system, such as Javadoc or Pydoc, that has a consistent appearance and structure.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] However, the types of content included in the documentation differs from API to API.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] In the interest of clarity, API documentation may include a description of classes and methods in the API as well as typical usage scenarios, code snippets, design rationales, performance discussions, and contracts, but implementation details of the API services themselves are usually omitted.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] It can take a number of forms, including instructional documents, tutorials, and reference works.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] It'll also include a variety of information types, including guides and functionalities.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Restrictions and limitations on how the API can be used are also covered by the documentation.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] For instance, documentation for an API function could note that its parameters cannot be null, that the function itself is not thread safe.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Because API documentation tends to be comprehensive, it is a challenge for writers to keep the documentation updated and for users to read it carefully, potentially yielding bugs.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] API documentation can be enriched with metadata information like Java annotations.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] This metadata can be used by the compiler, tools, and by the *run-time* environment to implement custom behaviors or custom handling.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] It is possible to generate API documentation in a data-driven manner.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] By observing many programs that use a given API, it is possible to infer the typical usages, as well the required contracts and directives.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Then, templates can be used to generate natural language from the mined data.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] In 2010, Oracle Corporation sued Google for having distributed a new implementation of Java embedded in the Android operating system.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Google had not acquired any permission to reproduce the Java API, although permission had been given to the similar OpenJDK project.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Judge William Alsup ruled in the *Oracle v.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Alsup's ruling was overturned in 2014 on appeal to the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit, though the question of whether such use of APIs constitutes fair use was left unresolved.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] In 2016, following a two-week trial, a jury determined that Google's reimplementation of the Java API constituted fair use, but Oracle vowed to appeal the decision.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Oracle won on its appeal, with the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit ruling that Google's use of the APIs did not qualify for fair use.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] In 2019, Google appealed to the Supreme Court of the United States over both the copyrightability and fair use rulings, and the Supreme Court granted review.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the oral hearings in the case were delayed until October 2020.
[src:gcp-apigee/api] The case was decided by the Supreme Court in Google's favor.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] Another meaning of "monetization" denotes the process by which the U.S.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] Treasury accounts for the face value of outstanding coinage.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] This procedure can extend even to one-of-a-kind situations such as when the Treasury Department sold an extremely rare 1933 Double Eagle.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] The coin's nominal value of $20 was added to the final sale price, reflecting the fact that the coin was considered to have been issued into circulation as a result of the transaction.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] In some industry sectors such as high technology and marketing, monetization is a buzzword for adapting non-revenue-generating assets to generate revenue.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] Such commodities as gold, diamonds, and emeralds have generally been regarded by human populations as having an intrinsic value within that population based on their rarity or quality and thus provide a premium not associated with fiat currency unless that currency is "promissory".
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] That is, the currency promises to deliver a given amount of a recognized commodity of a universally (globally) agreed-to rarity and value, providing the currency with the foundation of legitimacy or value.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] Though rarely the case with paper currency, even intrinsically relatively worthless items or commodities can be made into money, so long as they are challenging to make or acquire.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] Debt monetization is the financing of government spending by the central bank.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] In the latter case, the central bank may purchase government bonds by conducting an open market purchase, i.e. by increasing the monetary base through the money creation process.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] If government bonds that have come due are held by the central bank, the central bank will return any funds paid to it back to the treasury.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] Thus, the treasury may "borrow" money without needing to repay it.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] This process of financing government spending is called "monetizing the debt".
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] In most high-income countries the government assigns exclusive power to issue its national currency to a central bank, but central banks may be forbidden by law from purchasing debt directly from the government.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] For example, the Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union (article 123) forbids EU central banks' direct purchase of debt of EU public bodies such as national governments.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] Web sites and mobile apps that generate revenue are often monetized via online advertisements, subscription fees, or (in the case of apps) in-app purchases.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] In the music industry, monetization is achieved by placing ads before, after, or in the middle of content on a platform that supports this or posting the music on on-demand apps like Spotify and Apple Music.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] On-demand content sites like Spotify and Apple Music pay the artist a percentage of the monthly subscription fees they receive from their users.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] To put release music on streaming apps like Spotify and Apple Music, an artist has to reach out to a distributor like TuneCore or Distrokid.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] They are the one who do make the music available on streaming sites.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] This is usually done for a percentage of the revenue generation.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] For each public viewing, the advertising revenue is shared with the artist or others who hold rights to the video content.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] A previously free product may have premium options added thus becoming freemium.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] Businesses monetize their value propositions to generate the resources necessary for continued operation through a business model or revenue model.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] Failure to monetize websites due to an inadequate revenue model was a problem that caused many businesses to fold during the dot-com bust.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] Equally, David Sands, CTO for Citibank Equity Research, affirmed that failure to achieve monetization of the Research Analysts' models as the reason the de-bundling of Equity Research has never taken hold.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] On the other hand, aggressive monetization refers to how a firm or business is overemphasizing the process of making money at the cost of the user's well-being.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] The over-emphasis generate equal resistance from the users due to perceived unfairness and psychological reactance.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] Monetization is also used to refer to the process of converting some benefit received in non-monetary form (such as milk) into a monetary payment.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] The term is used in social welfare reform when converting in-kind payments (such as food stamps or other free benefits) into some "equivalent" cash payment.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] From the point of view of economics and efficiency, it is usually considered better to give someone a monetary equivalent of some benefit than the benefit (say, a liter of milk) in kind.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] In 2005, Russia transformed most of its in-kind benefits into monetary compensation.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] This system was a legacy of the Soviet Union, but it was heavily extended by populist laws passed by central and regional authorities during the 1990s.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] A wave of protests emerged in various parts of Russia in the beginning of 2005 as this law started to take effect.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] The government responded with measures that eventually addressed the most pressing of the protesters' concerns (raising of compensations, normalization of bureaucratic mechanisms, etc.).
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] The long-term effects of the monetization reform varied for different groups.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] Transport companies and railroads have benefitted from monetization as they now collect higher revenue from the use their services by pensioners who had previously ridden at the government's expense.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] (In some regions, more than half of the passengers formerly did not pay for municipal transport, but the government did not compensate the transport companies for the full fare of these passengers.) Effects on the medical system are controversial.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] Doctors and nurses have to fill out many forms in order to receive compensation from the government for services provided to pensioners, thus reducing the time that they have to provide medical services.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] In United States agricultural policy, "monetization" is a P.L.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] 480 provision (section 203) first included in the Food Security Act of 1985 (P.L.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] 99–198) that allows private voluntary organizations and cooperatives to sell a percentage of donated P.L.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] 480 commodities in the recipient country or in countries in the same region.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] Under section 203, private voluntary organizations or cooperatives are permitted to sell (i.e., monetize) for local currencies or dollars an amount of commodities equal to not less than 15% of the total amount of commodities distributed in any fiscal year in a country.
[src:gcp-apigee/monetization] The currency generated by these sales can then be used: to finance internal transportation, storage, or distribution of commodities; to implement development projects; or to invest and with the interest earned used to finance distribution costs or projects.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] In computer networking, a **proxy server** is a intermediary server application between a client requesting a resource and the server then providing that resource.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Instead of connecting directly to a server that can fulfil a request for a resource, such as a file or web page, the client directs the request to the proxy server, which evaluates the request and performs the required network transactions.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] This serves as a method to control the complexity of the request or provide additional benefits such as load balancing, privacy or security.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Proxies were devised to add structure and encapsulation to distributed systems.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] A proxy server may reside on the user's **local computer**, or at any point between the user's computer and the destination servers.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] A proxy server that passes unmodified requests and responses is usually called a gateway or sometimes a *tunneling proxy*.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] A forward proxy is an Internet-facing proxy used to retrieve data from a wide range of sources (in most cases, anywhere on the Internet).
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] A reverse proxy is usually an internal-facing proxy used as a front-end to control and protect access to a server on a private network.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] A reverse proxy commonly also performs tasks such as load-balancing, authentication, decryption, and caching.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] An open proxy is a forwarding proxy server that is accessible by any Internet user.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] In 2008, network security expert Gordon Lyon estimated that "hundreds of thousands" of open proxies are operated on the Internet.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] A reverse proxy (or surrogate) is a proxy server that appears to clients to be an ordinary server.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Reverse proxies send requests to one or more ordinary servers that handle the request.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] The response from the original server is returned as if it came directly from the proxy server, leaving the client with no knowledge of the original server.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Reverse proxies are installed in the vicinity of one or more web servers.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] All traffic coming from the Internet and with a destination of one of the neighborhood's web servers goes through the proxy server.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] The use of "reverse" originates in its counterpart, the "forward" proxy.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] The reverse proxy sits closer to the web server and serves only a restricted set of websites.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] A forward proxy is a server that routes traffic between clients and another system, which is, in most cases, external to the network.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] This means it can regulate traffic according to preset policies, convert and mask client IP addresses, enforce security protocols, and block unknown traffic.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] A forward proxy enhances security and policy enforcement within an internal network.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] A reverse proxy, instead of protecting the client, is used to protect the servers.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] A reverse proxy accepts a request from a client, forwards that request to another one of many other servers, and then returns the results from the server that specifically processed the request to the client.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Effectively, a reverse proxy acts as a gateway between clients, users, and application servers and handles all the traffic routing whilst also protecting the identity of the server that physically processes the request.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] A content-filtering web proxy server provides administrative control over the content that may be relayed in one or both directions through the proxy.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] It is commonly used in both commercial and non-commercial organizations (especially schools) to ensure that Internet usage conforms to acceptable use policy.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Content filtering proxy servers will often support user authentication to control web access.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] It also usually produces logs, either to give detailed information about the URLs accessed by specific users or to monitor bandwidth usage statistics.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] It may also communicate to daemon-based or ICAP-based antivirus software to provide security against viruses and other malware by scanning incoming content in real-time before it enters the network.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Many workplaces, schools, and colleges restrict websites and online services that are accessible and available in their buildings.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Governments also censor undesirable content.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] This is done either with a specialized proxy, called a content filter (both commercial and free products are available), or by using a cache-extension protocol such as ICAP, which allows plug-in extensions to an open caching architecture.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Websites commonly used by students to circumvent filters and access blocked content often include a proxy, from which the user can then access the websites that the filter is trying to block.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Requests may be filtered by several methods, such as a URL or DNS blacklists, URL regex filtering, MIME filtering, or content keyword filtering.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Blacklists are often provided and maintained by web-filtering companies, often grouped into categories (pornography, gambling, shopping, social networks, etc.).
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] The proxy then fetches the content, assuming the requested URL is acceptable.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] At this point, a dynamic filter may be applied on the return path.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] For example, JPEG files could be blocked based on fleshtone matches, or language filters could dynamically detect unwanted language.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] If the content is rejected, then an HTTP fetch error may be returned to the requester.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Most web filtering companies use an internet-wide crawling robot that assesses the likelihood that content is a certain type.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Manual labor is used to correct the resultant database based on complaints or known flaws in the content-matching algorithms.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Some proxies scan outbound content, e.g., for data loss prevention, or scan content for malicious software.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Web filtering proxies are not able to peer inside secure sockets HTTP transactions, assuming the chain-of-trust of SSL/TLS (Transport Layer Security) has not been tampered with.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] The SSL/TLS chain-of-trust relies on trusted root certificate authorities.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] In a workplace setting where the client is managed by the organization, devices may be configured to trust a root certificate whose private key is known to the proxy.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] In such situations, proxy analysis of the contents of an SSL/TLS transaction becomes possible.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] The proxy is effectively operating a man-in-the-middle attack, allowed by the client's trust of a root certificate that the proxy owns.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] If the destination server filters content based on the origin of the request, the use of a proxy can circumvent this filter.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] For example, a server using IP-based geolocation to restrict its service to a certain country can be accessed using a proxy located in that country to access the service.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Web proxies are the most common means of bypassing government censorship, although no more than 3% of Internet users use any circumvention tools.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Some proxy service providers allow businesses access to their proxy network for rerouting traffic for business intelligence purposes.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] In some cases, users can circumvent proxies that filter using blacklists by using services designed to proxy information from a non-blacklisted location.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Proxies can be installed to eavesdrop upon the data-flow between client machines and the web.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] All content sent or accessed, including passwords submitted and cookies used, can be captured and analyzed by the proxy operator.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] For this reason, passwords to online services (such as webmail and banking) should always be exchanged over a cryptographically secured connection, such as SSL.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] By chaining the proxies that do not reveal data about the original requester, it is possible to obfuscate activities from the eyes of the user's destination.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] However, more traces will be left on the intermediate hops, which could be used or offered up to trace the user's activities.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] If the policies and administrators of these other proxies are unknown, the user may fall victim to a false sense of security just because those details are out of sight and mind.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] In what is more of an inconvenience than a risk, proxy users may find themselves being blocked from certain websites, as numerous forums and websites block IP addresses from proxies known to have spammed or trolled the site.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Proxy bouncing can be used to maintain privacy.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] A **caching proxy** server accelerates service requests by retrieving the content saved from a previous request made by the same client or even other clients.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Caching proxies keep local copies of frequently requested resources, allowing large organizations to significantly reduce their upstream bandwidth usage and costs, while significantly increasing performance.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Most ISPs and large businesses have a caching proxy.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Caching proxies were the first kind of proxy server.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Web proxies are commonly used to cache web pages from a web server.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Poorly implemented caching proxies can cause problems, such as an inability to use user authentication.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] A proxy that is designed to mitigate specific link-related issues or degradation is a Performance Enhancing Proxy (PEPs).
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] These are typically used to improve TCP performance in the presence of high round-trip times or high packet loss (such as wireless or mobile phone networks); or highly asymmetric links featuring very different upload and download rates.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] PEPs can make more efficient use of the network, for example, by merging TCP ACKs (acknowledgements) or compressing data sent at the application layer.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] A translation proxy is a proxy server that is used to localize a website experience for different markets.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Traffic from the global audience is routed through the translation proxy to the source website.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] As visitors browse the proxied site, requests go back to the source site where pages are rendered.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] The original language content in the response is replaced by the translated content as it passes back through the proxy.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] The translations used in a translation proxy can be either machine translation, human translation, or a combination of machine and human translation.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Different translation proxy implementations have different capabilities.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Some allow further customization of the source site for the local audiences, such as excluding the source content or substituting the source content with the original local content.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] An anonymous proxy server (sometimes called a web proxy) generally attempts to anonymize web surfing.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Anonymizers may be differentiated into several varieties.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] The destination server (the server that ultimately satisfies the web request) receives requests from the anonymizing proxy server and thus does not receive information about the end user's address.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] The requests are not anonymous to the anonymizing proxy server, however, and so a degree of trust is present between the proxy server and the user.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Many proxy servers are funded through a continuous advertising link to the user.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Advertisers use proxy servers for validating, checking, and quality assuring geotargeted ads.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] A geotargeting ad server checks the request source IP address and uses a geo-IP database to determine the geographic source of requests.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Using a proxy server that is physically located inside a specific country or a city gives advertisers the ability to test geotargeted ads.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] A proxy can keep the internal network structure of a company secret by using network address translation, which can help the security of the internal network.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] This makes requests from machines and users on the local network anonymous.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Proxies can also be combined with firewalls.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] An incorrectly configured proxy can provide access to a network otherwise isolated from the Internet.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Proxies allow websites to make web requests to externally hosted resources (e.g., images, music files, etc.) when cross-domain restrictions prohibit the website from linking directly to the outside domains.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Proxies also allow the browser to make web requests to externally hosted content on behalf of a website when cross-domain restrictions (in place to protect websites from the likes of data theft) prohibit the browser from directly accessing the outside domains.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Secondary market brokers use web proxy servers to circumvent restrictions on online purchases of limited products such as limited sneakers or tickets.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] The request from the client is the same as a regular HTTP request except the full URL is passed, instead of just the path.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] This request is sent to the proxy server, the proxy makes the request specified, and returns the response.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Some web proxies allow the HTTP CONNECT method to set up forwarding of arbitrary data through the connection; a common policy is to only forward port 443 to allow HTTPS traffic.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Examples of web proxy servers include Apache (with mod_proxy or Traffic Server), HAProxy, IIS configured as proxy (e.g., with Application Request Routing), Nginx, Privoxy, Squid, Varnish (reverse proxy only), WinGate, Ziproxy, Tinyproxy, RabbIT and Polipo.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] For clients, the problem of complex or multiple proxy-servers is solved by a client-server Proxy auto-config protocol (*PAC file*).
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Various operating systems (such as Windows, Android, macOS, iOS, Xbox OS and PlayStation OS) and various browsers (such as Edge, Chrome, Safari and Firefox) can support Web proxy.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] SOCKS also forwards arbitrary data after a connection phase, and is similar to HTTP CONNECT in web proxies.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] An **intercepting proxy** redirects or filters client traffic without being explicitly selected by the client.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] It is therefore often deployed without requiring browser or application proxy settings, and clients may be unaware that their traffic is passing through a proxy.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] In HTTP terminology, an interception proxy differs from a conventional HTTP proxy because it is not chosen by the user agent; instead, it is placed in the network path and filters or redirects outgoing traffic, commonly TCP port 80 traffic.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] TCP Intercept is a traffic filtering security feature that protects TCP servers from TCP SYN flood attacks, which are a type of denial-of-service attack.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] TCP Intercept is available for IP traffic only.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] In 2009 a security flaw in the way that transparent proxies operate was published by Robert Auger, and the Computer Emergency Response Team issued an advisory listing dozens of affected transparent and intercepting proxy servers.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Intercepting proxies are commonly used in businesses to enforce acceptable use policies and to ease administrative overheads since no client browser configuration is required.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] This second reason, however, is mitigated by features such as Active Directory group policy, or DHCP and automatic proxy detection.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Intercepting proxies are also commonly used by ISPs in some countries to save upstream bandwidth and improve customer response times by caching.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] This is more common in countries where bandwidth is more limited (e.g, island nations) or must be paid for.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] The diversion or interception of a TCP connection creates several issues.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] First, the original destination IP and port must somehow be communicated to the proxy.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] This is not always possible (e.g., where the gateway and proxy reside on different hosts).
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] There is a class of cross-site attacks that depend on certain behaviors of intercepting proxies that do not check or have access to information about the original (intercepted) destination.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] This problem may be resolved by using an integrated packet-level and application-level appliance or software, which is then able to communicate this information between the packet handler and the proxy.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Intercepting also creates problems for HTTP authentication, especially connection-oriented authentication such as NTLM, as the client browser believes it is talking to a server rather than a proxy.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] This can cause problems where an intercepting proxy requires authentication, and then the user connects to a site that also requires authentication.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Finally, intercepting connections can cause problems for HTTP caches, as some requests and responses become uncacheable by a shared cache.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] In integrated firewall/proxy servers where the router/firewall is on the same host as the proxy, communicating original destination information can be done by any method, for example, Microsoft TMG or WinGate.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Interception can also be performed using Cisco's WCCP (Web Cache Control Protocol).
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] This proprietary protocol resides on the router and is configured from the cache, allowing the cache to determine what ports and traffic are sent to it via transparent redirection from the router.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] This redirection can occur in one of two ways: GRE tunneling (OSI Layer 3) or MAC rewrites (OSI Layer 2).
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Once traffic reaches the proxy machine itself, interception is commonly performed with NAT (Network Address Translation).
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Such setups are invisible to the client browser, but leave the proxy visible to the web server and other devices on the internet side of the proxy.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Recent Linux and some BSD releases provide TPROXY (transparent proxy), which performs IP-level (OSI Layer 3) transparent interception and spoofing of outbound traffic, hiding the proxy IP address from other network devices.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] A CGI web proxy accepts target URLs using a Web form in the user's browser window, processes the request, and returns the results to the user's browser.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Consequently, it can be used on a device or network that does not allow "true" proxy settings to be changed.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] The first recorded CGI proxy, named "rover" at the time but renamed in 1998 to "CGIProxy", was developed by American computer scientist James Marshall in early 1996 for an article in "Unix Review" by Rich Morin.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] The majority of CGI proxies are powered by one of CGIProxy (written in the Perl language), Glype (written in the PHP language), or PHProxy (written in the PHP language).
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] As of April 2016, CGIProxy has received about two million downloads, Glype has received more than half a million downloads, whilst PHProxy still receives hundreds of downloads per week.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Despite waning in popularity due to VPNs and other privacy methods, as of September 2021 there are still a few hundred CGI proxies online.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Some CGI proxies were set up for purposes such as making websites more accessible to disabled people, but have since been shut down due to excessive traffic, usually caused by a third party advertising the service as a means to bypass local filtering.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Since many of these users do not care about the collateral damage they are causing, it became necessary for organizations to hide their proxies, disclosing the URLs only to those who take the trouble to contact the organization and demonstrate a genuine need.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] A suffix proxy allows a user to access web content by appending the name of the proxy server to the URL of the requested content (e.g., "en.wikipedia.org.*SuffixProxy.com*").
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Suffix proxy servers are easier to use than regular proxy servers, but they do not offer high levels of anonymity, and their primary use is for bypassing web filters.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] However, this is rarely used due to more advanced web filters.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Tor is a system intended to provide online anonymity.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Tor client software routes Internet traffic through a worldwide volunteer network of servers for concealing a user's computer location or usage from someone conducting network surveillance or traffic analysis.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Using Tor makes tracing Internet activity more difficult, and is intended to protect users' personal freedom and their online privacy.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] This reduces the possibility of the original data being unscrambled or understood in transit.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] The I2P anonymous network ('I2P') is a proxy network aiming at online anonymity.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] It implements garlic routing, which is an enhancement of Tor's onion routing.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] I2P is fully distributed and works by encrypting all communications in various layers and relaying them through a network of routers run by volunteers in various locations.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] By keeping the source of the information hidden, I2P offers censorship resistance.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] The goals of I2P are to protect users' personal freedom, privacy, and ability to conduct confidential business.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Each user of I2P runs an I2P router on their computer (node).
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] The I2P router takes care of finding other peers and building anonymizing tunnels through them.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] I2P provides proxies for all protocols (HTTP, IRC, SOCKS, ...).
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] The proxy concept refers to a layer-7 application in the OSI reference model.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Network address translation (NAT) is similar to a proxy but operates in layer 3.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] In the client configuration of layer-3 NAT, configuring the gateway is sufficient.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] However, for the client configuration of a layer-7 proxy, the destination of the packets that the client generates must always be the proxy server (layer 7), then the proxy server reads each packet and finds out the true destination.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Because NAT operates at layer 3, it is less resource-intensive than the layer-7 proxy, but also less flexible.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] As we compare these two technologies, we might encounter a terminology known as 'transparent firewall'.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] **Transparent firewall** means that the proxy uses the layer-7 proxy advantages without the knowledge of the client.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] The client presumes that the gateway is a NAT in layer 3, and it does not have any idea about the inside of the packet, but through this method, the layer-3 packets are sent to the layer-7 proxy for investigation.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] A DNS proxy server takes DNS queries from a (usually local) network and forwards them to an Internet Domain Name Server.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Some client programs "SOCKS-ify" requests, which allows adaptation of any networked software to connect to external networks via certain types of proxy servers (mostly SOCKS).
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] A residential proxy (RESIP) is an intermediary that uses a real IP address provided by an Internet service provider with physical devices such as mobile phones and end-user computers.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Instead of connecting directly to a server, residential proxy users connect to the target through residential IP addresses.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] The target then identifies them as organic internet users.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] It does not let any tracking tool identify the reallocation of the user.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Any residential proxy can send any number of concurrent requests, and IP addresses are directly related to a specific region.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Unlike regular residential proxies, which hide the user's real IP address behind another IP address, rotating residential proxies, also known as *backconnect proxies*, conceal the user's real IP address behind a pool of proxies.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] These proxies switch between themselves at every session or at regular intervals.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Despite providers' assertions that the proxy hosts are voluntarily participating, numerous proxies are operated on potentially compromised hosts, including Internet of things devices.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] Through the process of cross-referencing the hosts, researchers have identified and analyzed logs that have been classified as potentially unwanted program and exposed a range of unauthorized activities conducted by RESIP hosts.
[src:gcp-apigee/proxy-server] These activities encompassed illegal promotion, fast fluxing, phishing, hosting malware, and more.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] In software engineering, **service-oriented architecture** (**SOA**) is an architectural style that focuses on discrete services instead of a monolithic design.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] SOA is a good choice for system integration.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] By consequence, it is also applied in the field of software design where services are provided to the other components by application components, through a communication protocol over a network.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] A service is a discrete unit of functionality that can be accessed remotely and acted upon and updated independently, such as retrieving a credit card statement online.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] SOA is also intended to be independent of vendors, products and technologies.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] Service orientation is a way of thinking in terms of services and service-based development and the outcomes of services.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] It is a black box for its consumers, meaning the consumer does not have to be aware of the service's inner workings.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] Different services can be used in conjunction as a service mesh to provide the functionality of a large software application, a principle SOA shares with modular programming.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] Service-oriented architecture integrates distributed, separately maintained and deployed software components.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] It is enabled by technologies and standards that facilitate components' communication and cooperation over a network, especially over an IP network.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] SOA is related to the idea of an API (application programming interface), an interface or communication protocol between different parts of a computer program intended to simplify the implementation and maintenance of software.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] An API can be thought of as the service, and the SOA the architecture that allows the service to operate.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] Note that Service-Oriented Architecture must not be confused with Service Based Architecture as those are two different architectural styles.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] In SOA, services use protocols that describe how they pass and parse messages using description metadata.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] This metadata describes both the functional characteristics of the service and quality-of-service characteristics.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] Service-oriented architecture aims to allow users to combine large chunks of functionality to form applications which are built purely from existing services and combining them in an ad hoc manner.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] A service presents a simple interface to the requester that abstracts away the underlying complexity acting as a black box.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] Further users can also access these independent services without any knowledge of their internal implementation.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] The related buzzword service-orientation promotes *loose coupling* between services.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] SOA separates functions into distinct units, or services, which developers make accessible over a network in order to allow users to combine and reuse them in the production of applications.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] These services and their corresponding consumers communicate with each other by passing data in a well-defined, shared format, or by coordinating an activity between two or more services.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] SOA can be seen as part of the continuum which ranges from the older concept of distributed computing and modular programming, through SOA, and on to practices of mashups, SaaS, and cloud computing (which some see as the offspring of SOA).
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] There are no industry standards relating to the exact composition of a service-oriented architecture, although many industry sources have published their own principles.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] documents within a given set of services.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] The relationship between services is minimized to the level that they are only aware of their existence.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] Services can be called from anywhere within the network that it is located no matter where it is present.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] Services should be designed to be long lived.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] Where possible, services should avoid forcing consumers to change if they do not require new features; if you call a service today, you should be able to call the same service tomorrow.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] The services act as black boxes, that is their inner logic is hidden from the consumers.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] Services are independent and control the functionality they encapsulate, from a Design-time and a run-time perspective.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] Services are stateless, that is either return the requested value or give an exception hence minimizing resource use.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] A principle to ensure services have an adequate size and scope.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] The functionality provided by the service to the user must be relevant.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] Services are decomposed or consolidated (normalized) to minimize redundancy.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] These are the cases where performance optimization, access, and aggregation are required.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] Services can be used to compose other services.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] Services are supplemented with communicative meta data by which they can be effectively discovered and interpreted.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] Logic is divided into various services, to promote reuse of code.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] Many services which were not initially planned under SOA, may get encapsulated or become a part of SOA.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] It creates a web service and provides its information to the service registry.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] and what sort of trading partner agreements are required to use the service.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] Its main functionality is to make information regarding the web service available to any potential requester.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] Whoever implements the broker decides the scope of the broker.
[src:gcp-apigee/service-oriented-architecture] Public brokers are available anywhere and everywhere but private brokers are only available to a limited amount of public.
