[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] A **software development kit** (**SDK**) is a collection of software development tools in one installable package.
[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] They facilitate the creation of applications by having a compiler, debugger and sometimes a software framework.
[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] They are normally specific to a hardware platform and operating system combination.
[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] To create applications with advanced functionalities such as advertisements, push notifications, etc., most application software developers use specific software development kits.
[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] Some SDKs are required for developing a platform-specific app.
[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] For example, the development of an Android app on the Java platform requires a Java Development Kit.
[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] For iOS applications (apps) the iOS SDK is required.
[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] For Universal Windows Platform the .NET Framework SDK might be used.
[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] There are also SDKs that add additional features and can be installed in apps to provide analytics, data about application activity, and monetization options.
[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] Some prominent creators of these types of SDKs include Google, Smaato, InMobi, and Facebook.
[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] An SDK can take the form of application programming interfaces in the form of on-device libraries of reusable functions used to interface to a particular programming language, or it may be as complex as hardware-specific tools that can communicate with a particular embedded system.
[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] Common tools include debugging facilities and other utilities, often presented in an integrated development environment.
[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] SDKs may include sample software and/or technical notes along with documentation, and tutorials to help clarify points made by the primary reference material.
[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] Platform SDKs may be distributed as multiple installable components rather than as a single monolithic package.
[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] For example, the Android SDK is composed of multiple packages required for app development, and its `sdkmanager` command-line tool can view, install, update and uninstall SDK packages.
[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] Microsoft's Windows SDK similarly includes platform headers, libraries, Windows Runtime metadata and build tools for developing Windows applications.
[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] SDKs often include licenses that make them unsuitable for building software intended to be developed under an incompatible license.
[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] For example, a proprietary SDK is generally incompatible with free software development, while a GNU General Public License'd SDK could be incompatible with proprietary software development, for legal reasons.
[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] However, SDKs built under the GNU Lesser General Public License are typically usable for proprietary development.
[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] In cases where the underlying technology is new, SDKs may include hardware.
[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] For example, AirTag's 2012 near-field communication SDK included both the paying and the reading halves of the necessary hardware stack.
[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] The average Android mobile app implements 15.6 separate SDKs, with gaming apps implementing on average 17.5 different SDKs.
[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] The most popular SDK categories for Android mobile apps are analytics and advertising.
[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] SDKs can be unsafe (because they are implemented within apps yet run separate code).
[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] Malicious SDKs (with honest intentions or not) can violate users' data privacy, damage app performance, or even cause apps to be banned from Google Play or the App Store.
[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] New technologies allow app developers to control and monitor client SDKs in real time.
[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] Providers of SDKs for specific systems or subsystems sometimes substitute a more specific term instead of *software*.
[src:gcp-apigee/software-development-kit] For instance, both Microsoft and Citrix provide a driver development kit for developing device drivers.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] In a web service, a web technology such as HTTP is used for transferring machine-readable file formats such as XML and JSON.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] In practice, a web service commonly provides an object-oriented web-based interface to a database server, utilized for example by another web server, or by a mobile app, that provides a user interface to the end-user.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] Many organizations that provide data in formatted HTML pages will also provide that data on their server as XML or JSON, often through a Web service to allow syndication.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] Another application offered to the end-user may be a mashup, where a Web server consumes several Web services at different machines and compiles the content into one user interface.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] Asynchronous JavaScript and XML (AJAX) is a dominant technology for Web services.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] Developing from the combination of HTTP servers, JavaScript clients and Plain Old XML (as distinct from SOAP and W3C Web Services), now it is frequently used with JSON as well as, or instead of, XML.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] Representational State Transfer (REST) is an architecture for well-behaved Web services that can function at Internet scale.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] A Web API is a development in Web services where emphasis has been moving to simpler representational state transfer (REST) based communications.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] Restful APIs do not require XML-based Web service protocols (SOAP and WSDL) to support their interfaces.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] W3C Web Services may use SOAP over HTTP protocol, allowing less costly (more efficient) interactions over the Internet than via proprietary solutions like EDI/B2B.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] Besides SOAP over HTTP, Web services can also be implemented on other reliable transport mechanisms like FTP.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] The term "Web service" describes a standardized way of integrating Web-based applications using the XML, SOAP, WSDL and UDDI open standards over an Internet Protocol backbone.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] XML is the data format used to contain the data and provide metadata around it, SOAP is used to transfer the data, WSDL is used for describing the services available and UDDI lists what services are available.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] A Web service is a method of communication between two electronic devices over a network.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] It is a software function provided at a network address over the Web with the service *always-on* as in the concept of utility computing.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] Many organizations use multiple software systems for management.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] Different software systems often need to exchange data with each other, and a Web service is a method of communication that allows two software systems to exchange this data over the Internet.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] The software system that requests data is called a *service requester*, whereas the software system that would process the request and provide the data is called a *service provider*.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] Different software may use different programming languages, and hence there is a need for a method of data exchange that doesn't depend upon a particular programming language.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] Most types of software can, however, interpret XML tags.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] Thus, Web services can use XML files for data exchange.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] All of these rules for communication are defined in a file called WSDL (Web Services Description Language), which has a `.wsdl` extension.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] A directory called UDDI (Universal Description, Discovery, and Integration) defines which software system should be contacted for which type of data.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] So when one software system needs one particular report/data, it would go to the UDDI and find out which other systems it can contact for receiving that data.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] Once the software system finds out which other systems it should contact, it would then contact that system using a special protocol called SOAP (Simple Object Access Protocol).
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] The service provider system would first validate the data request by referring to the WSDL file, and then process the request and send the data under the SOAP protocol.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] Automated tools can aid in the creation of a Web service.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] For services using WSDL, it is possible to either automatically generate WSDL for existing classes (a bottom-up model) or to generate a class skeleton given existing WSDL (a top-down model).
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] Critics of non-RESTful Web services often complain that they are too complex and based upon large software vendors or integrators, rather than typical open source implementations.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] There are also concerns about performance due to Web services' use of XML as a message format and SOAP/HTTP in enveloping and transporting.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] Functional and non-functional testing of Web services is done with the help of WSDL parsing.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] Regression testing is performed by identifying the changes made to upgrade software.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] Web service regression testing needs can be categorized in three different ways, namely, changes in WSDL, changes in the code, and selective re-testing of operations.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] We can capture the above three needs in three intermediate forms of Subset WSDL, namely, Difference WSDL (DWSDL), Unit WSDL (UWSDL), and Reduced WSDL (RWSDL), respectively.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] These three Subset WSDLs are then combined to form Combined WSDL (CWSDL) that is further used for regression testing of the Web service.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] This will help in Automated Web Service Change Management (AWSCM), by performing the selection of the relevant test cases to construct a reduced test suite from the old test suite.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] Web services testing can also be automated using several test automation tools like SoapUI, Oracle Application Testing Suite (OATS), Unified Functional Testing, Selenium, etc.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] Work-related to the capture and visualization of changes made to a Web service.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] Visualization and computation of changes can be done in the form of intermediate artifacts (Subset WSDL).
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] The insight on the computation of change impact is helpful in testing, top-down development and reduce regression testing.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] AWSCM is a tool that can identify subset operations in a WSDL file to construct a subset WSDL.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] While UDDI was intended to serve as a service directory and become the means to discovering web services, many vendors discontinued their UDDI solutions or repositories between 2005 and 2008, including Microsoft, SAP, IBM, among others.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] A key study published in WWW2008 Conference (Beijing, China) presented the state of SOAP-based web services and concluded that only 63% of the available SOAP-based web services at the time of the study were actually active or can be invoked.
[src:gcp-apigee/web-service] The study also found that search engines were becoming an ideal source for searching for web services compared to that of service registries like the UDDI due its design complexity.
